# Loom

Loom is a literate programming framework. You write a document — prose and code together, in the order that reads best — and Loom tangles it, composing the code into real source files. The prose is not documentation wrapped around the code but part of the program: the layer a person reads to learn what the code does and why.

This book is written in Loom, in the framework's own source, and it is the framework's only specification: the design notes that once sat apart from the code now live here, in the chapters that describe it, where they cannot drift. `loom weave` renders the book as the website you are reading — every chapter a page, its prose and its code side by side. Read it from the front. It opens with using Loom, then opens the machine, each part building on the one before.

# Table of Contents {TOC}

### Part I — Using Loom

You meet Loom the way you use it: by writing a document and watching it become code. This part is the whole surface a person touches, and nothing beneath it. It begins with a single loom and grows to a real project — sections composed with anchors and warps, one narrative spread across many files and languages, a workspace Loom sets up for you, and a command line that drives the rest. It is authored last, once the machine it introduces has settled.

### Part II — How a loom becomes code

You have written a loom; this part is what Loom makes of it. Loom is a literate-programming language, and a loom weaves three layers into one file: the **Loom syntax** that composes the document, the **prose** a person reads, and the **code** each section is written in. Loom reads the file into one tree and carries it along a chain of small, total passes, then composes that tree into its **product** — the author's code with every `::[…]` anchor resolved to an edge. The tangler writes the product to files; the editor reads the same tree. The rest of the book walks that pipeline one pass at a time.

1. The first syntax

### Part III — The shape of a loom

A loom is text, but Loom does not work on text. It works on a tree. This part is that tree — the data model every later pass reads and enriches.

