### Part IV — Reading the text

A loom arrives as plain text, and Loom must read it into the tree the previous part described. This part is that reading — four passes that turn text into a document, and a fifth that follows the document's imports out to its corpus.

1. Line ranges
2. The classifier stage
3. The tokeniser stage
4. The document builder
5. Building one module

### Part V — The product

Here the document becomes code. Each section carries the author's code, and each `::[…]` anchor says how that code composes; this part is the pass that reads the one and follows the other.

1. The product pass
2. The shape of the product

### Part VI — Tangling

With the product built, Loom writes it out. This part is the back half of the pipeline: the compiler that projects the result, the tangler that writes each file, the configuration that governs the build, the cache beneath it, and the one catalog of every fault.

